Value: Mostly in fair condition; top half of fol. 1, top middle of fols. 2-3 and bottom part of fol. 18 are torn off; fols. 19v-20r are stuck together; occasional stains and holes.

Sparsely dotted; rare vowel marks (e.g. fol. 2r); occasional šaddas , maddas; more regular vocalization of fatḥa tanwīn. Occasional Tiberian vowel signs for Hebrew written in Arabic script (e.g. fol. 6r, l. 11; 17v, l. 11; and see the description of other fragments belonging to the same codex); Divine Name written as ادوناي; sparsely dotted; occasional ihmāl-marks; uses an isolated hāʾ with backwards swinging tale (e.g. 2v, l. 4).

Containing Commentary on the Pentateuch (fols 1–16), Joshua (fol. 17), Jeremiah (18r-33), Ezekiel (fols 33v-42r), Minor Prophets (fols 42r-65v), Chronicles (fols 65v-73v), Psalms (fols 73v-99v), Job (fols 99v-130r), Proverbs (fols 130r-141v), Esther (fols 141v-143v), Daniel (fols 143v-149r, 152–159), Ezra (fols 149, 160–162), Song of Songs (fols 150-151) and Nehemiah (fols 162-165).
Well preserved with the exception of fol. 16* (torn off at top, bottom and outer margin).

Rare vowel marks; Divine Name rendered as اذوناي (e.g. fol. 11v, l. 12; see also description of other fragments belonging to the same codex); sparsely dotted; occasional ihmāl-marks. Hebrew in Arabic script, including lengthy quotations from the Mishnah (mRH), more frequently dotted (e.g. 14r, ll. 4-18).

Occasionally dotted;  vowel marks here and there (e.g. fol. 18r); occasional šaddas , maddas; more regular vocalization of fatḥa tanwīn;  Divine Name rendered as ﯨﯩﺎ (e.g. fols. 5r, l. 3; 8v, l. 13);  isolated hāʾ with backwards swinging tale at end of textual units and chapters (e.g. fols. 4v, ll. 4, 6, 8, 11; 6r, l. 3 ; 6v, l. 8).

Sparsely dotted; rare vowel marks; Divine Name written as ادوناي (e.g. fol. 2r, l. 2); sparsely dotted; occasional ihmāl-marks; circled dot at the end of chapter and chapter headings and textual units (e.g. fol 4r, ll. 11, 13).

Fols. 1-2 are two consecutive folios of a quinion quire; fol. 3 belongs to the subsequent quire and follows immediately after Arab.-Yevr. 250, fol. 1r (reversed folio!) and precedes Arab.-Yevr. 276, fol. 1 (q.v.).

Almost fully dotted; frequent vowel marks and fully vocalised in places (e.g. fol. 3v, ll. 5-11); šaddas, maddas, and hamzas. Frequent Tiberian vowel signs in red ink for Hebrew written in Arabic script (e.g. fol. 1v, l. 5); Divine Name rendered as اذوناي (see Arab.-Yevr. 250); abundantly dotted; frequent ihmāl-marks; circled dot at the end of textual units and chapters (e.g. fol. 2v, ll. 3, 8).

An acrostic piyyuṭ beginning יער עד צור / יסוד חיוה דיערא, with the name Yefet b. ʿEli in the acrostic in a different hand (3r). At the top of the folio a blessing in large letters. Possibly, the end of a commentary on Proverbs (colophon on fol. 3r).

Quire signatures as Hebrew numerals in the upper right corner of the first recto page: 12 (יח); 20 (יט); 30 (כ); 40 (כא); 50 (כב); 60 (כג); 70 ([כ]ד). Catchwords in the lower left corner of the last verso: fols. 11; 19; 29; 39.
The manuscript has suffered somewhat. Traces of worm damage found throughout (fols. 1–14, 36–51, 67–68, 80–86); larger tears and other damages have been filled in (fols. 1–14).
Possibly also an abridgement of Salmon b. Yeruḥam’s (?) Commentaries, see title on fol. 39v), containing Commentary on the Book of Ecclesiastes (fol. 2r) and Lamentations (fol. 2v).
Containing a Commentary on the Book of Exodus 16 (see incipits of Ex. 16:24 on fol. 14r and Ex. 16:35 on fol. 14v).

Sparsely dotted; rare vowel marks (e.g. fol. 2r); occasional šaddas , maddas; more regular vocalization of fatḥa tanwīn. Occasional Tiberian vowel signs for Hebrew written in Arabic script (e.g. fol. 1r, l. 1; 6r, l. 8); Divine Name written as ادوناي;  occasional ihmāl-marks; circled dot at the end of chapters and chapter headings (e.g. fol. 1r, ll. 7, 12; 14r, ll. 5, 9).

Containing the 9th discourse on forbidden sexual relations (fols 1-2), 3rd discourse on the new moon (fol. 3). Title page of the 9th discourse (fol. 1r). Below the title of the 9th discourse on fol. 1r, there is another note in Arabic script introducing the second exposition on the aviv and the harvest (קציר).
Containing discourse 1 (on circumcision; fols 57r–64v) and discourse 8 (on ritual purity; fol. 66r–v) (?).

Rare vowel marks (e.g. fol. 2r); occasional šaddas, maddas; more regular vocalization of fatḥa tanwīn. Occasional Tiberian vowel signs for Hebrew written in Arabic script (e.g. 13r, l. 3); sparsely dotted; occasional ihmāl-marks;  circled dot at the end of chapter and chapter headings (e.g. fol. 6v, ll. 2, 4).
Binding holes and threads (e.g. fols. 32v-33r; fols. 41v-42r).
In good condition; torn off at the top margin; faded at top of fol. 1r and 6v.

Rare vowel marks; Divine Name rendered as اذوناي (see description of other fragments belonging to the same codex); sparsely dotted; occasional ihmāl-marks; isolated hāʾ (mostly without dot or tale) at end of textual units and chapters (e.g. fol. 2v, l. 9).
Well-preserved; torn off at the upper inner and lower outer corners of fols. 1-4; slightly worm-eaten.
